The paper focuses on high-dimensional inference problems and their connection to information theory, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also discusses the standard linear model, which is a common topic in Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Statistical Inference (cs.SI). The use of the replica method from statistical physics suggests that the paper may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on understanding phase transitions in high-dimensional inference problems suggests that it may also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
